:[]},{"name":"third","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["Scottish: locative name from one or more of various minor places so called because they were at one time farms divided among three tenants."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Lord","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: nickname from Middle English <i>laford</i>, <i>louerd</i>, <i>lord</i> ‘lord, master’ (Old English <i>hlāford</i>), perhaps given to a someone who played the part of the lord or master of ceremonies in festival games.","Irish: adoption of the English name (see 1 above) as a translation of the main element of Gaelic <b>Ó Tighearnaigh</b> (see   Tierney  ) and <b>Mac Thighearnáin</b> (see   McKiernan  ).","Americanized form of French <b>Laure</b>, a variant of the personal name   Laur   3."],"variants":[{"name":"Tierney","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Brendan, Eamon, John Patrick, Brigid, Clodagh, Kieran, Michael Sean, Siobhan.","Irish: shortened form of <b>O'Tierney</b>, an Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Tíghearnaigh</b> ‘descendant of <i>Tighearnach</i>’, a byname meaning ‘lord, master’. The Gaelic name is sometimes ‘translated’ as English   Lord  . Compare   Tiernan  ."]},{"name":"Lords","meanings":["English: variant of   Lord  , with post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>. This surname is rare in Britain."]}]},{"name":"Borthwick","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Scottish: habitational name from the old barony of Borthwick, formerly Loquhariot (Midlothian) and possibly also from Borthwick (Roxburghshire). The placenames are from Old English <i>bord</i> ‘board, table’ + <i>wīc</i> ‘outlying dairy farm’."],"variants":[]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir William Borthwick third Lord Borthwick was born in 1440, his father, Sir William Borthwick, II Lord Borthworth, was 35 and his mother, Mariote De Hoppringill, was 15. He had at least 1 daughter with Name Not Unkown. He died in 1513, in Branxton, Northumberland, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 73."},"et":{"1440–1513":"1440–1513","1418–1454":"1418–1454","1465–1505":"1465–1505","1405–1503":"1405–1503","1425–1473":"1425–1473","1503":"1503","1513":"1513","1425":"1425","8 February 1473":"8. veebruar 1473","1454":"1454","1465":"1465","1440":"1440","1473":"1473","1418":"1418","1505":"1505","1405":"1405","Flooden, near Branxton, Northumberland, Kingdom of England not part of the United Kingdom":"Branxton, Northumberland, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Borthwick, Midlothian, Scotland":"Borthwick, Midlothian, Šotimaa, United Kingdom","Suffolk, England":"Suffolk, England","Wales, England":"Wales, South Yorkshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1440–1513":"1440–1513","1418–1454":"1418–1454","1465–1505":"1465–1505","1405–1503":"1405–1503","1425–1473":"1425–1473","1503":"1503","1513":"1513","1425":"1425","8 February 1473":"8. helmikuuta 1473","1454":"1454","1465":"1465","1440":"1440","1473":"1473","1418":"1418","1505":"1505","1405":"1405","Flooden, near Branxton, Northumberland, Kingdom of England not part of the U